nd present case studies that grapple with issues of class struggle, gentrification, violence against women, and Indigenous rights. Going Public offers insights into long-standing concerns around voice, aesthetics, appropriation, privilege, power dynamics, and the ethics of participation. It reveals that the shift towards participatory research and creative practices requires a commitment to asking tough questions about oneself and the ways that people’s stories are used.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAction research. 0aArtistsvInterviews. 0aArts and society. 0aOral historyxSocial aspects. 0aParticipant observation. 0aResearchxSocial aspects. 0aSocial scientistsvInterviews. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / General.2bisacsh1 aHigh, Steven, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aHigh, Steven, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLittle, Edward (Ted), econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLittle, Edward, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aMiller, Elizabeth (Liz), econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311127363108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2018z978311127598708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of British Columbia Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311141792940uhttps://doi.org/10.59962/978077483664740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780774836647423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780774836647/original  a978-3-11-127363-1  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  a978-3-11-127598-7  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2018b2018  a978-3-11-141792-9  University of British Columbia Complete eBook-Package 2018